The first lines in any light source should be:
 
#include <mudlib.h>
#include <treasure.h>
#include <material.h>
inherit LIGHT;
 
These lines set up the object to be a light source and will
allow calls to the light master object as defined below.
 
--------------------
 
set_name("name");
 
        string name.  Adds the name passed in to the id list.
 
set_alias("alias");
 
        string alias.  This is another name for the object.  It doesn't
        appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.
 
set_alt_name("alt_name");
 
        string alt_name.  This is yet another name for the object.
        It doesn't appear anywhere, but it can be used by the player.
 
set_short("short");
 
        string short.  This is the description seen in the player's
        inventory.
 
set_long("long.\n");
 
        string long.  Sets the long description of the object to long.
       I added the ".\n" in the LPC line above to remind you that you
       should add the period and newline in the long description
       because LPC doesn't add it in for you.  This is what the player
       will see when they look at the object.
 
set_weight(weight);
        integer weight.  This is the weight of the object.
 
set_treasure_type(TYP_LIGHT|TYPE2|...);
 
        Needless to say, you must at the very least set the treasure type
        to TYP_LIGHT.  If there ere other properties to the light, they
        should be added as well.
 
set_material(TYPE1|TYPE2|...);
 
        bitfield TYPE1, TYPE2, ....
 
set_max_fuel(int);
 
        The integer amount for the maximum amount of fuel the object can
        hold. If this line is left out, it will default to 1000.
        IMPORTANT: This line MUST go before the line set_fuel() line.
 
set_fuel(int);
 
        This is the amount of fuel that the light source will start with.
        For every 1 point of fuel, the light source will stay lit for 2
        seconds.  So a set_fuel(30) would stay lit for 1 minute.
        IMPORTANT: This line must go after set_max_fuel();
 
add_fuel(int);
 
       This will add fuel to light source upto a maximum of max_fuel.
       this function will almost always be called from an external
       source for the purpose of refilling a light source.
 
set_reusable(int);
 
       Is the object reusable, or will it burn itself up in the process of
       being used.
         1 = reusable;
         0 = burns up in use.
       If this line is left out, it will default to burn itself up in use.
 
set_can_light(int);
 
        Is the object always on, or can it be turned on and off.  The flag
        is as follows:
          1 = can be lit and extinguished.
          0 = is always on.
        If this line is left out, it will default to being able to be lit.
        If object is always on, you don't need either set_max_fuel,
        set_fuel, or set_reusable.  If an object is always on, this
        variable needs to be set BEFORE set_power();
 
set_value(value);
 
        integer value.  This is the selling value of the object.  The
        buyback value is twice this value.  Also, the amount of fuel left
        in the object will modify the value of the object if it uses fuel.
        Please note, that the value is determined by a light source with
        a full supply of fuel.  So if you set_value of 100 but then only
        put 1/4 of the fuel in it to fill it, you will get a reduced price.
 
set_power(int);
 
        How much light does the light source give off?  Default is 1.
 
set_read("object","message.\n");
 
        string read.  This is what the player will see if they read the
        object.  I added the ".\n" in the LPC line above to remind you
        that you should add the period and newline in the long description
        because LPC doesn't add it in for you.
 
set_info("info.\n");
 
        string info.  This will be displayed to the owner of the object
        if he identifies it.  This line is required on all objects magical
        or mundane.  This is a good place to put special information about
        the object that a player would not normally have access to.
        A hint of the weight could be given, as well as if the object has
        any special uses.  If the item is truely a mundane item, state in
        the set_info that there are no special properties with the item.
 
set_no_buy(n);
 
        status n.  Set this to 0 if you want people to be able to
        buy and sell this to and from the store.  Set to 1 if you
        don't.  If you don't set this command, it will default to
        buyable.
 

void set_no_sell(int iX);

Pass a 1 as the parameter to have it be refused in stores. Note that this
works a bit differently from no_buy, in that the more times you call
set_no_sell(1), the more times you then have to call set_no_sell(0) to
get it to a sellable state again. This is done so that the creator can
set it no_sell, and if a guild uses no_sell to prohibit players from selling
checked-out/borrowed items, when the guild calls set_no_sell(0) when the
object is done being borrowed, the item will still not be sellable.

int query_no_sell(); 


Returns sellable status.
set_steal(n)
 
        status n. Set to 1 if you want to make the item unstealable
        by thieves.  Don't abuse this command!  It is meant only for
        things like quest items or objects great importance.  If you
        don't add this command, item defaults to stealable
